tip.text:
It may seem like everyone and their grandma is transforming an abandoned East End railway arch into something or other, but you can't fault Night Tales for their ambition. Set in two arches and an accompanying outdoor area that encompass almost 6,000 square feet, this is a huge Hackney hangout spot offering plenty. There's an Asahi beer garden, covered and heated seating areas, live music from a 300-capacity club space, a large cocktail bar, a beer shack, an in-house Japanese Izakaya restaurant (Fat Baby) and pizza (Sons of Slice).

They've battened down the hatches for winter, covering their huge covered terrace and adding some fire pits, candles and, fear not, dependable heaters pumping out warmth. Just don't think too much about that energy bill. Liable to get lively on weekend evenings, head here for a little hibernation, Hackney style.

We could spend all day in this incredible store. And, luckily, we can. A coffee shop and fully-stocked bar enable round-the-clock fun (parties, exhibitions, illustration classes and open-mic nights). This feels like the kind of venture you should support, a place with real soul.

You’ll find wow-inducing women’s clothing, shoes and accessories from 1900s–80s. It’s great for dresses and there are even some bridal bits. Expect an in-house tailor and seamstress specialising in vintage alterations and a personal shopper on hand too. Upstairs the men’s selection is slightly smaller but still cool. Come for the clobber, stay for the cocktails.

Oslo is a no-chance-of-failure kind of place; a late night Hackney staple. Downstairs is a lively restaurant/bar where you can enjoy Nordic themed grub with interesting craft beers and well made cocktails. But this place is really about the upstairs - a music/gig/club/get-crunk space where you can carry the night on later than you really ought to. If you hit it really hard upstairs, there's a chicken shop bang opposite which (at 3am) glows like some kind of mirage in the night.

What was once a boozer with a dodgy rep on the Murder Mile has gradually earned its place in people's hearts as a loveable, slightly scruffy community hub with hella soul. There’s been no million-pound facelift here (or however much pub facelifts cost), instead, you’ll find a creaking tavern with plenty of nooks and crannies adorned in random vintage bits and bobs, worn floorboards, log fires and mismatched furniture.

This is a big pub with the intimacy and charm of a small one: where weekly comedy nights are legendary and a late Saturday night pitstop will be rewarded with an unpretentious raucous dance to Wham or suchlike. Add in one of the biggest beer gardens in East and you’ve got yourself all you require from a neighbourhood boozer.

Moth Club - short 'of course' for The Memorable Order of Tin Hats - is a wondrously kitsch time warp of a boozer and event space. It’s a glittery mash-up of two cultural scenes colliding: an ex-servicemen’s club whose members still shoot the shit and play darts in the old bar whilst a sprightly and unsightly blend of Hackney young’uns come and embrace a lil' joyous abandon.

Nice indie gigs, 80s nights, bingo, themed quizzes (Peep Show, Ru Paul, Simpsons...) and film screenings take place under the gold glittered ceiling, amid red velvet booths and the iconic red and black chequered floor. Yep it's got the aesthetic, but it's also got the kind of welcoming vibe that’ll have you spinning around to Abba at midnight without a care in the goddamn world.

Found down a narrow-ish street amongst the bustle of Hackney lies The Gun, everything you want your local boozer to be and more. In some form or another the pub itself has been serving pints of the good stuff for Hackney patrons since 1860, but in its latest guise The Gun offers hearty food, locally sourced ales and spirits, arguably the city's greatest pub quiz, and some of the best pub dogs to stroke in all of LDN.

They also welcome a weekly rotation of some of London's finest DJ talent all in the confines of a cozy east end drinkery; with DJs spinning from Thursday to Sunday and dancing heavily encouraged. From tropical disco for your end of week celebration to Sunday selections to calm your soul, The Gun offers a night on the tiles without taking a big knock to your bank balance.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

A proper Hackney institution, The Dolphin is the night-ender. It’s beer sodden, it’s loud and it’s a little bit smelly - only advisable when you're several drinks down and frantically searching for somewhere to go at 1am and looking to get down to 00's R'n'B hits. Don’t come here looking for high grade craft beer or champagne cocktails, but do expect to have a few tales to tell the next morning. If you can remember them. They also do regular karaoke here and have a free jukebox.

Formerly the rather ramshackle London Fields Pub, this building has had a significant refurb to become Martello Hall: a three storey townhouse that serves as a cocktail bar, restaurant, workspace and on-the-go coffeehouse. Plenty of dough has been spent on the stripped-back decor and vintage furniture, and the result is a pretty swanky and classy joint.

Food wise, it's mostly Italian fare with sharing plates and a wood fire oven for delicious pizzas. We'd particularly recommend the Number 7, with roast squash & beetroot, ricotta, hazelnuts, beetroot pesto, mint and kale. Upstairs, you'll find a cosy lounge area with decks and a cocktail bar, which seems an ideal place to woo and be wooed as the night unfolds.

What else? You can hot desk here and work, and also grab coffee or sausage roll by the inch from their street hatch.

The well-loved pop-up Night Tales has taken the leap into brick and mortar to give you NT’s Bar. Make the trek up the several flights of stairs and be greeted to an impressive open plan space adorned with plants and all things millennial. With huge windows and a south-facing roof terrace, this makes for an ideal spot to watch the sunset over the city- cocktail in hand, of course.

Cocktails here are no nonsense - inventive but classy - with all cordials, infusions and shrubs made in house. You might be paying a little more for the view, location and oozin' cool but by George is it worth it.

There ain't no party quite like a Victoria party. Away from the charming, vomit-laden streets of Dalston Kingsland lies weekend favourite, The Victoria, a typical east end boozer with a difference. Offering the staple hangover-friendly meals of burgers, fries, hot dogs and other meaty essentials, behind a book case at the back of the pub lies one of London's most underrated venues; hosting live performances and free club nights most days of the week.

Owned by The Jaguar Shoes Collective, The Victoria is a vital staple for those in search of no frills attached fun, the type of place where one pint can easily turn into 6 or 7 before you've had chance to think 'how hungover will this make me tomorrow?' The answer is very... very hungover.

Like your mum at a wedding, The Shacklewell Arms is a beautiful, sweaty mess - and we love her for it. From peeling astroturf in the graffitied garden and dripping taps in the rank toilets; to the noisy pub in the front and the humid, low-ceilinged event space in the back, the place exudes scruffy charm with only the smallest helping of pretension. It rocks and it rolls and occasionally it does both at once.

It’s run by the minds that bring us Field Day every year, so you’ll often catch up-and-coming acts that, in a couple of years when they blow, you can say you saw in a dingy Hackney pub - which is just the boost your rapidly dwindling stock of social capital could use.

Located on Ridley Road Market, this tropical dance box is the place to wear whatever the hell you want and dance however the hell you like. If you can't vogue like Madonna on this 80s-style dance-floor, then when can you? Once at the bar, get your hands on a Ginger Mojito, because big cocktails are better than little ones and because Ginger Mojitos are even tastier than they sound and at £5 you surely can't go wrong. Bear in mind, this place is completely cash-free so bring your card and leave your penny jar at home.

If there ever was a basement that feels nothing like a basement, but really is just a basement, it'd be VFD. There are no decorations to speak of, the loos have swinging doors and no locks, the bar is big enough for three skinny bartenders and the dance floor can fit maybe 40 people, tops. It's grimy, it's sweaty, and yet it's so much fun.

This alternative basement plays host to some of the quirkiest nights, with everything from die-ins, spiritual rituals, spoken word nights, drag acts, erotic salons and cool pop-electro-camp-tastic club nights like Sassitude, Dirty Diana or Straight Nasty. It's pretty hit and miss at times, but it's so intimate that you can't help but have a good time.

Be warned: VFD only opens when it has an event going on, so double check before heading there.

We're into Victory Mansion and its offering of tasty Asian tacos and offbeat cocktails. This is a laid-back, hand-built bar in Stokey that's got a swish mid-century feel to it. It's apparently paying homage to the literature, food and drink that's inspired London over the last century and comes with the appropriate dim lighting, dark woods and 70s-inspired basement parlour.

The tacos, bright and bold in flavour, feature the likes of torched seabream, fermented yellow bean leeks and nahm jim chicken. These are recipes above the usual fodder and sized for sharing (read: not that big). They're also bottomless on the weekends when brunch brings the business.

The cocktails, meanwhile, are seriously impressive - both in concept and taste. There's a large menu of imaginative, unique concoctions broken down into different chapters (Hero Hi-balls, Villainous Shorts, Crazy Coupes...) and clearly a lot of focus has been putting together these recipes. We dig that. What else to say? That the basement is a fine place for a late night drink or private party.

Farr's treads a distinct line between charming local boozer, staple Sunday afternoon spot and antiques emporium. Old telephone boxes, vintage record players, trombones, hairdresser chairs and whatever form of bric-a-brac you can imagine decorates every nook & cranny in this Dalston cornerstone.

But what about the booze? Thankfully, Farr's offers both style and substance as thirsty travellers can expect ales and IPAs from east London's favourite boozers and an extensive cocktail selection to boot. Foodies can indulge in their hearty selection of burgers, buns and Sunday roasts, while for the pub ravers DJs spin every Saturday from 8pm - 1am on their vinyl-only setup. Come for the decor, stay for the tunes, leave with no regrets... until the next morning, that is.

A place to get your game face on and feel right at home. Modelled on Tokyo's gamer cafes, this is a place to 'drink, relax and play'. Dojo likes doing all of that, but we've never tried them all at once. There are board games, retro arcade games and collaborative spaces where you can play on their consoles with other gamer sorts. Their drinks list is also game-inspired with 'World of Barcraft' and 'Rum Total War' among the strong bevvies on offer.

'A place where the bartender’s drink' is the type of compliment every cocktail bar secretly wants, so congratulations to High Water. This is the classier tip on this fairly wild strip, where cocktails are given real pride of place.

The intimate space itself has the ubiquitous raw bricks, dim lights and warm brown leather seats. But it also has a huge fake wooden ceiling; something that sounds a little tacky but kinda just works. It's like you’ve stumbled into a cosy bar in some remote part of Inverness or something. The cocktails, featuring plenty of signatures and classics, are really tip top and come in at around a tenner.

A vibrant institution in the Dalston scene, this cafe, bar and club gets pretty darn busy with all sorts of movers and shakers finding their way down into the basement. Popular with the LGBT crowd, the biggest draw is the eclectic music on offer with nights including everything from electro, Italo and disco, to 90's R&B and hip hop. Prices are rarely more than a fiver.

There’s a surprising lack of cocktail bars in Stoke Newington, but that’s OK as long as you have a spot like Original Sin. This subterranean drinking den is easily missed, but find the nondescript door on Stoke Newington High Street, slink down the steps and you’ll find yourself transported to a classier time.

The cocktails here are strong and expertly blended, the lights are low and you feel like you can speak freely about your most clandestine affairs. Their take on an old fashioned really goes down smooth. And their free pool table is probably the suavest place to play in North.
